    "Incorrectness, alongside non-comprehensiveness (as above), was the most common second-order code, identified in about 90% of studies (n = 78/89).",
    "In our conceptual synthesis of incorrect results, we followed the taxonomy of Currie et al.",
    "to classify incorrect outputs more precisely into illusions, delusions, delirium, confabulation, and extrapolation, thus proposing a framework for a more precise and structured error classification to improve the characterization of incorrect outputs and enabling more detailed performance comparisons with other research 43, 112, 113.",
